It turns out that he was sleep walking. I am not kidding when I say that he walked up the stairs slowly just like the girl from the movie who was being led by the ghost. On top of that, he kept moaning "MOM". Probably the scariest moment of my life.

text: I think what intrigues the most to genuine horror genre fans is the story and the screenplay. You can have the most ugliest or horrific looking ghost but if you can't build up that story behind it, the movie's a comedy. What James wan did right with The Conjuring was, he kept it simple, no stupid slashing murders or bloodbaths. He focused on the story and made us get 2 feet deeper into our own shell. Same with the Insidious, the movie was simple with no senseless scary ghosts appearing contrasting to the storyline. One other movie which has intrigues me right now is The Witch. I just can't get over that little boy mimicking goat's voice right into that goat's ear. This trailer revealed a bit more than it should. Any half brain human can predict the plot after that but still I'm gonna go for the movie.

text: Dear Warner Bros and any other Studio responsible for marketing and trailer editing an upcoming movie horror,  please stop showing the scary parts in the trailer. I don't know why you keep doing this, but stop it! You all better start developing the art and skill of teasing the scary parts throughout the marketing campaigns. I promise you, people will still go to see your movie. I am still going go see The Conjuring 2, but now I know what to expect from it.   And before anyone jumps on me about this, I am aware that maybe they haven't shown all the jump scares and completely spoiled them all, but imagine if they didn't show you the Nun, the Old Man, and the little girl's voice change during the interview. Imagine how much a surprise that would've been to say, "Holy crap! They didn't show this in the  trailer! This movie is so scary, I don't know what to expect!" Think about that for a minute.

text: This looks like great entertainment, but to get the real true story of the Enfield haunting read "This House is Haunted" by Guy Lyon Playfair.  He and Maurice Grosse were the true investigators, virtually living with the family for over a year.  The Warrens just breezed in and out for a day.  This film seems to take a lot of liberties.  There was no nun, no inverted crosses, no sticking to the ceiling etc.  There were enough remarkable events in the true story (Janet allegedly passing through a solid wall for instance). I don't see why they had to make things up for the film.  Still, it looks like great cinema, but if you really want to get the real scoop, read the book.  Also listen to the real voice recordings on Youtube.

text: Come on, these types of movies are overdone. The only things that can scare me in this movie are the jump scares(the most basic type of scare), but I expect most of them because they're so obvious. Needless to say, I'd still rather build a house than move in an old one. I don't believe in spirits, and neither am I particullarly religious, although I'd prefer not to discuss my beliefs, but I don't want to stumble into any supernatural things(which I believe are VERY real, although not in the inverted-cross-demon-sin-devil way, which sadly still seems to be the norm). Bye the way, here's a Pro-Tip on how NOT to get scared by ANY horror movie: Just imagine you're a critic watching it for a review. Focus on the camera-work, script, story-line, acting, special fx, anything that helps ease your fear. And make sure to bring a friend, you can take comfort in knowing that they're scared and you're not!(or at least you think you're not).

text: I'm so tired of scary movies resorting to "pop" scares, where something can only scare you if it pops out and makes you jump. There used to be an art in horror movies where the scares were provided by the sense of dread and terror associated with the scene, back when movies showed objects moving into peculiar places, or when sounds grew louder and such, now everything is boom! something jumps out, then ahh! something is in a reflection, theres no art in it anymore. I don't think filmmakers know how to properly scare people anymore. I kinda liked the way the first Insidious movie was made though, there wasn't too many pop scares, there was a lot of creativity in their method of creating terror. The Babadook comes to mind as a perfectly done horror movie.  Another thing about these conjuring movies is that its well known that the Warren couple were hoaxers and liars. Even people originally claiming to have a haunting had disagreed with how the warrens seemed to add details to their story that didn't actually happen. And for goodness sake's, the real Annabelle doll was a raggedy Anne doll, thats what made her so scary was that Raggedy Anne dolls were in stores everywhere and people were afraid they'd pick up an Annabelle for their child.  I'm not a hater of this movie, its just that I wish scary scenes made sense, but audiences don't seem to mind that the movies don't make sense, as long as they get their fill of the Jack-in-the-box scare method.

text: The upcoming movie "The Conjuring 2" is based on a true story. However the majority of events, scenes, plot, and theme in this movie are Far-fetched. After watching the trailer for this movie and reading about the true story of the Enfield Haunting, I must say there is a lot of Hollywood in this film. Which is not uncommon in films based on true stories but the trailer for this movie is way too misleading. For instance if you were to rate the Enfield Haunting event VS The Conjuring it would not be rated R. Also, two of the main actors in this film are Vera Farmiga and Patrick Wilson who play the part for Lorraine Warren and Ed Warren. However Ed and Lorraine Warren had little to none in investigating the Enfield Poltergeist case.

text: THE CONJURING 2 - Movie Commentaries & Reviews by: Alvin Sebetero Spoiler Level : VERY MINIMAL ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ The very 1st Conjuring movie made a very huge impact around the globe and many people even considered it as the Best Horror movie in history, including myself. So, the moment that they announced that the sequel will happen, expectation from people is really high. And how did the sequel did? --- I believe it certainly did very well too. I never expected the sequel to be so good. I don't want to compare which is best among the two because both are two different stories but the movies are both beautifully made and beautifully executed. What I loved about the sequel are: * The Characters - For both movies, what makes the Conjuring really good is how they were able to make the viewers feel connected with the Warren couples and the family involved. Every character in this sequel played their role perfectly. * The Story - The flow of the story is very clean and very detailed. The fact that it is based on a true story made it even better. And actually, the movie was very, very realistic when it comes to how they act to situations. There are very emotional moments that made me tear a little. There are funny moments, romantic moments and a lot of well-executed shock and terrifying moments. Another story that made me emotional is the story of the spirit of Bill Wilkins, it will make everyone realize the sadness of unexpected death. * The Values - This may be a horror movie, I would suggest this to be viewed by the whole family even the children. There are a lot of values to be learned such as valuing each members of your family and no matter what happen, be strong and fight for each other. The importance of life and how we should appreciate each and every moment. This movie is really unexpected for a horror movie. You will come out of the cinema happy and will definitely say, "What I paid for is all worth it" and I myself would even watch it again. The best moment is experiencing it with other viewers in the cinema. I never experienced the viewers to react that way and how loud they screamed, all the cursing and the reactions. It only shows that the movie is very, very effective and warning --- it may consume all your energy.
author: Alvin Sebetero

I always have questions when I watch horror movies. I will post all the questions below. If you think you can answer my questions, please do it in a comment below. I will be very grateful. Also, some questions might sound a little dumb, so don't mind me. [Spoiler Alert!] 1 Why did the Demon Nun want to kill Janet?  2 If she did want to kill her, why didn't she just kill her from the beginning instead of just trying to haunt the family? 3 Why was Janet the only one that could be possessed by the demon? 3 If Lorraine could use the bible to defeat the Demon by knowing her name, why was the Demon the one telling her name to her? (It's not like, "Hey, this is my name, you can use it to kill me." MEH -_-) 4 How did the Demon possess Bill? (I mean it makes sense if she possesses human, but possesses the same spirit? Like WTF?)  5 Also, wasn't the Demon in the United States at first? text: Good cinematography, actors, special effects, and tension build. It is beautifully filmed in dark & ominous colors. The music was tense, and the demon nun was freakishly scary. But I didn't see anything new here. This is the type of movie you can watch with a notebook and start checking the cliches as they appear. As this film is 110+ minutes long, you might get tired quickly of hearing a loud noise, scream, paranormal door slam, or furniture dash, because it happens a lot and gets old faster.  Overall enjoyable film, but terribly generic.

text: I have just watched this and this is a good film or could have been... IF it wasn't for the DREADFUL English accents by non English actors, not only that; they spoke in a terrible mockney accent.  Would it have been so hard considering that it was made by WB with no doubt a huge budget to get actors with the correct accents for where they came from, it totally distracted me throughout the whole film. If WB could afford to partially film in the UK (which they did) why couldn't they use English actors instead of using Australians,Americans and Germans for some of the main character roles. Also this was the 70's and NOBODY in the 70s in a lower working class family which is how they were depicted (single mum looking after a few kids on her own, and their bad representation of the accents they would have had etc) would have a television like that with a remote control. We and most people I know did not have a remote until well into the 80s and we were not poor, they just were not common like in the states.We say ''I think'' not ''I guess'' and the mum saying ''the city'' just was not correct she would have said ''the town'' I really wish these things had not have let down this film so badly as it could have been a great film had these accents been so diabolical that it distracted me from the story throughout.

text: I've seen "The Conjuring 2" and it was very scary. I'm glad that I went to see this movie without no expectations whatsoever and it really caught me with these haunted imagery that it really works. Director, James Wan (Who did recently "The Conjuring" and made other films like "Saw," "Insidious," and "Insidious, Chapter 2") knows who to make clever jump scares that it doesn't distract you when there's a silly thing or just a random character pops by, but it scares me with the strange poltergeist that I was freaked out. The film takes place in a true story that we left off the Warrens who are planning to help the family in England and it makes it so well that it is actually a clever true story which it knows the facts and making it realistic. The actors did a great and between Farmiga and Wilson manager their roles perfectly since they done from the last one. For me, it's the scariest sequel I had ever seen.

text: I wanna say something to anyone going to watch this movie. It is great until the warrens get involved. Iam almost immune to being scared of a movie but i must say, first hour i guess, off the movie i was a bit scared and jumpy. Something i havn't been in a very long time from movies. Which i was super happy about. But it all went down the drain when the warrens got involved. Because when they get involved it turned in to ALOT less scary and more into action/drama. I wasn't scared at all as soon as they got involved with the whole ordeal. Because it turned more into drama/romance between the wife and edd and how she had seen his death and was so afraid he would die and wanted to rescue him and he was all heroic like, it just went to shit. Btw these are no real spoilers, the death scene comes super early, i think u see it within the first 10mins of the movie. If they had kept the creepyness and how scary and hidden the main boogyman was, it would have been alot better. So less burst down every door in the house and more mystery and a more "clever" way to find the solution and the bottom off who the boogyman is and using more clever ways to beat him more than "spoiler" knowing the guys name and say i banish u to hell and done.   So my tldr: great movie till the warrens get involved, you will be scared until then, so if you only there for scary part, just watch until the warrens get to the house then end the movie. After that it's just drama/action.

text: I'm sorry, but even though James Wan(ker) may be a decent director of drama, as far as horror goes, he's, well, horrible!  The Conjuring 2 works very well whenever there's nothing scary going on. The scenes in England have a gritty kitchen sink feel to them, the young girl who sees everything is a great actress,  and Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga do a fine job of making a couple of real-life nutcases seem likeable.  The rest is just discounted jump scare after cheap jump scare. The same shit we've seen in horror films for far too long now.  The only people who might conceivably find this exciting are religious people, for whom seeing an evil nun is unthinkable, people who are afraid of naughty pensioners who are dementedly guarding their slippers, and very young children (but they're scared of everything, so they don't count).  The first film wasn't great. But compared to the usual trash, it did have a couple of effective scenes, and it did a good job of building up a foreboding atmosphere.  That's all gone this time around. This is Eastenders meets Ghosthunters, and it's every bit as bad as that sounds.  Let's hope the third one recaptures some of the qualities the first one had.

text: The movie is a cheesy bag of shit. Having read a lot about the Enfield Poltergeist, this is a dramatized (badly done too) pile of poo (Marilyn Manson nun? please!). The Warrens had almost no involvement in the case, Maurice Grosse and Guy Playfair did the majority of the hard work to help the family. Do yourselves a favour, do not watch this film, read the book, this house is haunted, and watch the documentary on Enfield (it was on Youtube), far more interesting and spooky than any jump-scare hollywood crap.  Some things were undoubtedly faked later by the kids but there was far too much real unexplained events to refute it as a true modern poltergeist case (despite what this movie says, it was considered a poltergeist case focused on Janet, not a haunted house/demon - that is why there are no reports of events in the house today).

text: I went to see this movie with 5 or 6 other college friends. It was one of the best movie experience. It was also a dark and rainy day. And while i returned all drenched in rain, a huge tree which fell down during the thunderstorm was blocking my way to my home. Also the power lines were damaged probably due to the fallen tree, and we had no power that day. So me and mom lit candles and i still can't imagine how i went to kitchen that night to get food.(mom was tired and slept all the night). And i finished dinner and went back to my room and placed the candle near my bed's window. And while i lied down on my bed, I really felt like Valak was  standing in the dark corner behind my bed. I chatted on messenger and whatsapp with my cousin but she fell asleep fast. So i was left with no choice but to go into sleep which i found the most difficult thing to do. But somehow i did and woke up the next day to bright sunlight and relief. Now when i think about it, that was one of the best as well as scariest days ever. I really wish i could go back in time to that day in June.

text: While I really enjoyed this movie, I feel like it wasn't nearly as scary as the first one, and it wasn't nearly as scary as the premise would make you think, especially with James Wan on board.  I feel like this movie went for a more...action/fantasy kind of feel.  Even the actual scary scenes...didn't feel HORROR, it felt "awesome", like "damn, this demon is badass".  It felt like they were trying to show the demons front and center in order to build up their cinematic universe.  I think they spent too much time juggling the three villains (even though the old man wasn't a villain, he was portrayed as such for the majority of the movie) to try to build their universe more and I think it makes the film feel disjointed, and it gave it more of a fantasy/action feel.  While this is cool, I do hope they stick more to the tone of the first Conjuring and Annabelle Creation rather than the tone for this movie, as I feel like it was a little bit off.  It felt a little bit too close to a superhero movie in the way that the villains kind of teamed up and the Warrens were kind of like superheroes.  I expect the Crooked Man movie to have more of a fantasy tone to it, which is totally fine and understandable, but the Nun movie better be like the first Conjuring, as the Nun is a genuinely scary character.  The tone that Conjuring 2 used should be saved for an eventual "team up" film.  The Conjuring 1, Annabelle and Annabelle Creation had a pure evil tone throughout, and i felt Conjuring 2 was sorely lacking in this aspect.  It's like they kept the horror elements there, but showed them in a more "look how cool this is" type of way.  Anyone else feel this way?

text: What I really hated about this movie was how they took the art from the first one, about Lorraine’s “vision” that terrified her and kept her in her bed for days. How Ed makes it out to be SO horrendous and evil that she will *never* discuss it. And then, in this one (part 2), they reveal that her “vision” was her husband Ed dying. Like, really?? What the fuck? I was SO pissed when I saw that. That part of the first one was probably the most disturbing part of the entire movie. But it ends up being something totally boring and stupid. Figures they would make it something that 1) doesn’t affect the audience in any way whatsoever, and 2) doesn’t really affect the movie at all.  I just totally feel like they ruined the entire franchise with that bullshit. I actually thought that that part affected the audience so much in the first one, that they could have easily made an entire part 3 based on that alone, Lorraine’s “vision”. At least, they could’ve if they made it about something scary.  Oh, and before some moronic American teenager tries saying “it’s a true story” well first of all, the Enfield Poltergeist was completely made up by that girl. None of it was real. Second, I don’t believe anything Ed and Lorraine did in real life. As they have been caught in a hoax several times over the course of their “careers”.  I think they have always been 100% full of shit. Even the Amityville Horror house was all a big giant hoax by the family that lived there. They admitted in later years, as did an author of a book based on the haunting. He said that the family who lived there had helped him make up various things that he could claim happened there. I bring this up because the Warrens has supposedly done extensive work on the Amityville haunting and had sworn that it was 100% haunted and they had seen evil things, etc etc etc once again, they are completely full of shit!

text: فيلم رعب رائع وجميل  لن أتكلم عنه فقد سبق وذكرت روعته وجماله . لكن بعض الأفلام من روعتها تجعلك تكررها أكثر من مرة مثل هذا سلسلة الفيلم : " الشعوذة " ، ومثل سلسلة أفلام : " مالفيسنت " وغيرها من روائع السينما العالمية .  طرح الفيلم قضية : " المس الجني للإنسان " عبر واقعة حقيقية لعائلة في لندن ١٩٧٧ ميلادي ، وبغض النظر عن كونها حقيقة أو مزيفة . لكن هناك من العرب من يؤمن ببعض أفكار النصاري مثل :- ١- حكماء اليونان مثل : أفلاطون وأرسطو وغيرها . ٢- " دافينشي " عندما رسم شكل الجنين في بطن أمه - في تلك الحقبة التي لا يوجد فيها مستشفيات - بالضبط مثل : " جهاز السونار " في المستشفيات الحديثة .  لكن برغم ذلك - مع أن دينهم محرف وباطل - فهم أعقل من : سفهاء الأحلام و - دعاة الضلالة - من المسلمين الذين ينكرون أشياء ذكرت في القرأن الكريم والسنة النبوية مثل :- ١- طه حسين : عندما أنكر نبوة سيدنا : إبراهيم وإسماعيل - عليهما السلام - ، وكذلك أنكر نبوة سيد الخلق : محمد - صلى الله عليه وسلم - . ٢- علي الطنطاوي - صاحب برنامج : على مائدة الأفطار - أنكر وجود الله في السماء في كتابه : " خطب منبرية " طبعة جدة . ٣- الترابي - الصوفي - أنكر عذاب القبر . ٤- المتخلفين - ممن يدعون العلم - أنكروا أنه يوجد هناك " مس الجن للإنسان " .
